refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
boolarray_key_exists stringintkey arrayarray
array_key_exists returns &true; if the given key is set in the array. key can be any value possible for an array index.

&reftitle.returnvalues;


 &return.success;




  array_key_exists will search for the keys in the first dimension only.
  Nested keys in multidimensional arrays will not be found.

  &reftitle.examples;



    array_key_exists example


<?php
$search_array = array('first' => 1, 'second' => 4);
if (array_key_exists('first', $search_array)) {
    echo "The 'first' element is in the array";
}
?>





   array_key_exists vs isset


    isset does not return &true; for array keys
    that correspond to a &null; value, while
    array_key_exists does.



<?php
$search_array = array('first' => null, 'second' => 4);

// returns false
isset($search_array['first']);

// returns true
array_key_exists('first', $search_array);
?>

&reftitle.notes;
For backward compatibility reasons, array_key_exists will also return &true; if key is a property defined within an object given as array. This behaviour is deprecated as of PHP 7.4.0, and removed as of PHP 8.0.0.
To check whether a property exists in an object, property_exists should be used.
